Note: ========================================
Note: Regex to HIR Translator
Note: ========================================
Note: Translates regex AST to Runa HIR
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/regex/regex_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/regex/regex_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

@Reasoning:
Regex parse trees are recursive (alternation of concatenations of quantified atoms); the top-level HIR envelope tags the document as a pattern and embeds the recursively translated root as its sole child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a Dictionary tagged type=regex_pattern, translate the AST root via translate_node, and attach the result at key "pattern".
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Regex sources are typically user-supplied; the translator does no compilation, so adversarial patterns cannot trigger ReDoS at this stage. Backreferences may be present and must be validated downstream against the actual group count.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_regex_to_hir" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "regex_pattern"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let pattern_key be proc create_string_literal with "pattern"
    Let pattern_value be proc translate_node with ast
    proc set from Dict with hir, pattern_key, pattern_value
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The regex AST encodes ten node kinds with the same physical layout but different semantic meanings; central dispatch keeps translate_regex_to_hir oblivious to the per-kind shape and lets every recursive call site share one entry point.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the tag at offset 0 and dispatch: 1->pattern, 2->alternation, 3->concatenation, 4->quantified, 5->group, 6->char_class, 7->literal, 8->anchor, 9->backreference, 10->dot. Null input or unknown tag returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_node" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    If node_type is equal to 1:  Note: REGEX_PATTERN
        Return proc translate_pattern with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 2:  Note: REGEX_ALTERNATION
        Return proc translate_alternation with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 3:  Note: REGEX_CONCATENATION
        Return proc translate_concatenation with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 4:  Note: REGEX_QUANTIFIED
        Return proc translate_quantified with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 5:  Note: REGEX_GROUP
        Return proc translate_group with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 6:  Note: REGEX_CHAR_CLASS
        Return proc translate_char_class with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 7:  Note: REGEX_LITERAL
        Return proc translate_literal with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 8:  Note: REGEX_ANCHOR
        Return proc translate_anchor with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 9:  Note: REGEX_BACKREFERENCE
        Return proc translate_backreference with node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 10:  Note: REGEX_DOT
        Return proc translate_dot with node
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The REGEX_PATTERN wrapper node has exactly one meaningful child (the root expression); this helper unwraps the envelope so callers see the pattern body directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the children List from offset 32. If there is at least one child, recursively translate child[0] and return it. Otherwise return an empty Dictionary so callers do not see null.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_pattern" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Return proc translate_node with child
    End If
    Return proc create from Dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
"a|b|c" forms an n-ary alternation rather than a left-leaning binary tree; emitting all branches as a flat list lets matchers build NFA epsilon-fans without re-walking nested OR structure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=alternation. Walk the AST children, recursively translate each into a HIR sub-Dictionary, and append non-null results to a List attached at key "branches".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_alternation" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "alternation"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let branches be proc create from List
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let branch_hir be proc translate_node with child
        If branch_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc push from List with branches, branch_hir
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let branches_key be proc create_string_literal with "branches"
    proc set from Dict with hir, branches_key, branches
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
"abc" forms an n-ary concatenation; an ordered List of elements preserves matching order without imposing a binary tree shape on downstream code generators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=concatenation. Walk children, recursively translate each, and append non-null results to a List attached at key "elements".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_concatenation" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "concatenation"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let elements be proc create from List
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let element_hir be proc translate_node with child
        If element_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc push from List with elements, element_hir
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let elements_key be proc create_string_literal with "elements"
    proc set from Dict with hir, elements_key, elements
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser encodes the quantifier in a metadata field as base + modifier-band: the base is 8 (*), 9 (+), 10 (?), or 11 (range {m,n}); the band is 0 (greedy), 30 (lazy '?' suffix), or 60 (possessive '+' suffix). The inner sub-expression is the single child. Translating both the base and the modifier into the fully-formed quantifier string (e.g. "*", "*?", "++", "{2,5}?") keeps the HIR self-describing and lets the backend blit the suffix verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read metadata at offset 24. Decode band = metadata - (metadata mod-30 partition): values >= 60 are possessive (modifier byte '+'/43), >= 30 are lazy (modifier byte '?'/63), else greedy (no modifier). The base is metadata minus the band. Map base 8/9/10 to the single bytes '*'/'+'/'?'; base 11 uses the "{m,n}" lexeme span from the node's value pointer. Build the quantifier string by copying the base bytes, appending the modifier byte when present, and NUL-terminating. Attach at key "quantifier". Translate the single inner child and attach at key "element".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_quantified" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "quantified"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24

    Note: Decode modifier band and base quantifier code.
    Let modifier_byte be 0
    Let band be 0
    If metadata is greater than or equal to 60:
        Set modifier_byte to 43  Note: '+' possessive
        Set band to 60
    Otherwise:
        If metadata is greater than or equal to 30:
            Set modifier_byte to 63  Note: '?' lazy
            Set band to 30
        End If
    End If
    Let base be metadata minus band

    Note: Resolve the base quantifier bytes (pointer + length).
    Let base_ptr be 0
    Let base_length be 0
    Let single_byte be 0
    If base is equal to 8:
        Set single_byte to 42  Note: '*'
        Set base_length to 1
    End If
    If base is equal to 9:
        Set single_byte to 43  Note: '+'
        Set base_length to 1
    End If
    If base is equal to 10:
        Set single_byte to 63  Note: '?'
        Set base_length to 1
    End If
    If base is equal to 11:
        Set base_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
        Set base_length to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    End If

    Note: Assemble base bytes + optional modifier byte + NUL.
    Let total_length be base_length
    If modifier_byte is not equal to 0:
        Set total_length to total_length plus 1
    End If
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with total_length plus 1
    If base is equal to 11:
        If base_ptr is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_copy from Layout with buffer, base_ptr, base_length
        End If
    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, 0, single_byte
    End If
    If modifier_byte is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, base_length, modifier_byte
    End If
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, total_length, 0

    Let quantifier_key be proc create_string_literal with "quantifier"
    proc set from Dict with hir, quantifier_key, buffer
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let element_hir be proc translate_node with child
        Let element_key be proc create_string_literal with "element"
        proc set from Dict with hir, element_key, element_hir
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Groups span seven flavours: capturing "(...)", non-capturing "(?:...)", named "(?<name>...)", and the four zero-width lookaround assertions positive/negative lookahead "(?=...)"/"(?!...)" and positive/negative lookbehind "(?<=...)"/"(?<!...)". The parser encodes the kind as the originating lexer token tag in metadata; the translator lifts it into a self-describing HIR string so the backend can reproduce the exact PCRE delimiter. For named groups the capture name is extracted from the opening lexeme so it survives the round trip.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=group. Read metadata at offset 24 and map: 17 -> "non_capturing", 18 -> "named", 19 -> "lookahead_pos", 20 -> "lookahead_neg", 21 -> "lookbehind_pos", 22 -> "lookbehind_neg", any other (15) -> "capturing". Attach at key "group_type". For a named group, extract the name between '<' and '>' from the node's opening lexeme (value pointer/length) and attach at key "name". Translate the single child sub-expression and attach at key "contents".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_group" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "group"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
    Let group_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "group_type"
    Let group_type_value be proc create_string_literal with "capturing"
    If metadata is equal to 17:
        Set group_type_value to proc create_string_literal with "non_capturing"
    End If
    If metadata is equal to 18:
        Set group_type_value to proc create_string_literal with "named"
    End If
    If metadata is equal to 19:
        Set group_type_value to proc create_string_literal with "lookahead_pos"
    End If
    If metadata is equal to 20:
        Set group_type_value to proc create_string_literal with "lookahead_neg"
    End If
    If metadata is equal to 21:
        Set group_type_value to proc create_string_literal with "lookbehind_pos"
    End If
    If metadata is equal to 22:
        Set group_type_value to proc create_string_literal with "lookbehind_neg"
    End If
    proc set from Dict with hir, group_type_key, group_type_value
    If metadata is equal to 18:
        Let lexeme_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
        Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
        Let name_str be proc extract_group_name with lexeme_ptr, lexeme_length
        If name_str is not equal to 0:
            Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
            proc set from Dict with hir, name_key, name_str
        End If
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let contents_hir be proc translate_node with child
        Let contents_key be proc create_string_literal with "contents"
        proc set from Dict with hir, contents_key, contents_hir
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A named group's opening lexeme is one of "(?<name>", "(?'name'", or "(?P<name>"; the name is the run of bytes between the opening delimiter ('<' or the apostrophe) and the matching closing delimiter ('>' or apostrophe). Extracting it into an owned null-terminated string lets the HIR carry the name independently of the source buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Scan the lexeme for the first '<' (60) or apostrophe (39); the byte after it begins the name. Continue until the closing '>' (62) or apostrophe (39) or end of lexeme; that bounds the name span. Materialise the span via regex_string_from_span. Return 0 when no opening delimiter is found so the caller omits the name key.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_group_name" takes lexeme_ptr as Integer, lexeme_length as Integer returns Integer:
    If lexeme_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If lexeme_length is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let name_start be 0 minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than lexeme_length:
        Let c be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme_ptr, i
        If c is equal to 60:  Note: <
            Set name_start to i plus 1
            Set i to lexeme_length
        Otherwise:
            If c is equal to 39:  Note: apostrophe
                Set name_start to i plus 1
                Set i to lexeme_length
            Otherwise:
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While
    If name_start is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let name_end be name_start
    Let j be name_start
    Let scanning be 1
    While scanning is equal to 1:
        If j is greater than or equal to lexeme_length:
            Set name_end to j
            Set scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let cc be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme_ptr, j
            If cc is equal to 62:  Note: >
                Set name_end to j
                Set scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                If cc is equal to 39:  Note: apostrophe
                    Set name_end to j
                    Set scanning to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Let name_length be name_end minus name_start
    If name_length is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let name_ptr be lexeme_ptr plus name_start
    Return proc regex_string_from_span with name_ptr, name_length
End Process

@Reasoning:
Character classes "[a-z]" carry their full bracketed lexeme in the parser node's value pointer; deferring expansion (range explosion, Unicode property lookup) to the matcher avoids encoding ISA-specific decisions in HIR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=char_class. If the node's value pointer and length are non-zero, materialise the lexeme as a String and attach at key "value".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_char_class" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "char_class"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    If value_ptr is not equal to 0:
        If value_length is greater than 0:
            Let value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
            Let value_str be proc regex_string_from_span with value_ptr, value_length
            proc set from Dict with hir, value_key, value_str
        End If
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A literal is the leaf case of the AST - a single matched character or escape sequence captured verbatim from the source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=literal with the lexeme materialised from the node's value pointer/length and attached at key "value".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_literal" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "literal"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    Let value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
    Let value_str be proc regex_string_from_span with value_ptr, value_length
    proc set from Dict with hir, value_key, value_str
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Anchors (^, $, \b, \B, \A, \z, ...) match zero-width positions; preserving the original anchor token as a string in HIR keeps the meaning explicit without imposing an enum.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=anchor with the anchor lexeme attached at key "value".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_anchor" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "anchor"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    Let value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
    Let value_str be proc regex_string_from_span with value_ptr, value_length
    proc set from Dict with hir, value_key, value_str
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Backreferences "\1", "\k<name>" reference an earlier capture group; the lexeme carries the group number or name as text, leaving validation against actual group count to later semantic analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=backreference with the reference lexeme attached at key "value".
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Backreferences enable non-regular matching that can drive catastrophic backtracking; the consumer must reject or budget-cap them on untrusted patterns.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_backreference" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "backreference"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    Let value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
    Let value_str be proc regex_string_from_span with value_ptr, value_length
    proc set from Dict with hir, value_key, value_str
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The "." meta-character matches one character (modulo s-flag handling for newlines); it has no lexeme payload so the HIR node carries only the discriminator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Return a Dictionary tagged type=dot with no further fields.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_dot" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create from Dict
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "dot"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Centralising string-literal construction lets future intern-table changes touch a single call site instead of every key allocation in the translator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_string_from_literal and return its pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lexeme views in the AST point into the original regex source buffer and are NOT individually null-terminated; HIR dictionary values must be standalone null-terminated strings so downstream emitters (which treat values as C-strings) read exactly the span. This helper materialises a fresh owned copy of a byte span and terminates it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate length+1 bytes, copy the span via memory_copy, write a terminating NUL at offset length, and return the new buffer. A null pointer or non-positive length yields a freshly allocated empty (single-NUL) string so callers never receive 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "regex_string_from_span" takes value_ptr as Integer, value_length as Integer returns Integer:
    If value_ptr is equal to 0:
        Let empty be proc allocate from Layout with 1
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with empty, 0, 0
        Return empty
    End If
    If value_length is less than 1:
        Let empty2 be proc allocate from Layout with 1
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with empty2, 0, 0
        Return empty2
    End If
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with value_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with buffer, value_ptr, value_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, value_length, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Single-Argument Source Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public single-arg facade invoked by the translation dispatcher's
LANG_REGEX arm. Wires the full source -> HIR pipeline: Lexer
create_lexer + tokenize produce a token stream, Parser create_parser
+ parse build the regex AST, and translate_regex_to_hir walks the
AST into HIR. Intermediate lexer and parser handles are released
deterministically so the wrapper has zero ownership effect on the
caller side.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
lexer = Lexer.create_lexer(source); Lexer.tokenize(lexer);
parser = Parser.create_parser(lexer); ast = Parser.parse(parser);
hir = translate_regex_to_hir(ast); Parser.destroy_parser(parser);
Lexer.destroy_lexer(lexer); return hir. On any parse failure
(ast == 0) the wrapper still tears down the lexer/parser and
returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "regex_to_hir_from_source" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source_code
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser
    Let hir_root be 0
    If ast is not equal to 0:
        Set hir_root to proc translate_regex_to_hir with ast
    End If
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return hir_root
End Process
